{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 15:17:39.067070", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and intent\n- Objective: Assess current network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root cause(s) without proposing mitigations.\n- Environment: Hierarchical OSPF-based enterprise network with access/distribution/core, DHCP relay to central server, DNS in 10.200.0.0/24, Apache web servers web0.local…web3.local, Nginx load balancer web99.local fronting backend web servers on a non-routed backend subnet.\n\nHigh-level health summary\n- Layer 3 reachability: Normal. All checked hosts and servers in 10.200.0.0/24 are reachable with low latency and no packet loss based on distributed ping tests.\n- OSPF routing: Implicitly healthy (end-to-end IP reachability from both access hosts to server farm subnets and consistent latencies across multiple paths). No symptomatic routing asymmetry or loss observed.\n- DNS resolution: Functional for clients. Client-side name resolution is quick with correct A records for web0.local (10.200.0.3), web1.local (10.200.0.4), and web99.local (10.200.0.7). Notable cosmetic issue on the DNS server’s local resolver with IPv6 (details below), but clients do resolve correctly.\n- HTTP services: Generally healthy for web1.local, web2.local, web3.local, and web99.local. Intermittent performance anomaly isolated to web0.local (10.200.0.3) with occasional very slow TTFB and outright timeouts.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) IP reachability and latency\n- Pings from access hosts to key servers:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): avg ~2.3 ms, 0% loss\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_1 (10.200.0.4): avg ~3.1 ms, 0% loss\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 0% loss, ~3.15 ms\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 0% loss, avg ~3.15 ms\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_1/dns_server: similar low-latency, 0% loss\n- No packet loss or anomalous latency spikes indicative of congestion or L3 instability along the client-to-server paths.\n\n2) DNS resolution\n- Client resolution:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 getent hosts: web0.local -> 10.200.0.3; web1.local -> 10.200.0.4; web99.local -> 10.200.0.7 (fast name lookup during curls: ~2–10 ms).\n- Server-side resolver behavior:\n  - On dns_server, “host” command outputs repeated “UDP setup with ::1#53(::1) … address not available” before ultimately resolving the names correctly. This indicates the tool attempted IPv6 localhost and failed, but IPv4 A record responses are ultimately correct. This did not affect client lookups.\n\n3) HTTP service behavior and performance\n- From both access hosts:\n  - web1.local / web2.local / web3.local:\n    - TTFB typically ~0.2–1.7 s; total ~1.0–2.5 s across runs. No timeouts observed.\n  - web99.local (Nginx load balancer):\n    - Stable performance across multiple runs: TTFB commonly ~0.22–0.68 s; total ~1.03–1.47 s.\n  - web0.local (10.200.0.3):\n    - Intermittent severe slowness and timeouts observed initially on both hosts:\n      - Two runs exceeded 10s timeout; subsequent run: namelookup ~4–10 ms, connect ~6–13 ms, starttransfer ~6.6–7.6 s, total ~7.4–8.4 s (very slow TTFB).\n    - Follow-up testing showed more typical performance:\n      - Later runs to http://web0.local and direct IP http://10.200.0.3 mostly TTFB ~0.4–1.9 s; total ~1.2–2.8 s.\n- Server-side checks on web_server_0 (10.200.0.3):\n  - Port 80 listening (python3) and reachable.\n  - Interface and IP stats normal: no errors/drops; tc fq_codel shows zero drops/overlimits; interface healthy.\n  - ICMP RTT stable and low (2–4 ms typical).\n- Interpretation: The slowdowns to web0.local are not due to DNS latency (namelookup fast), not due to L3 path loss/latency, and not due to NIC drops or traffic shaping. The symptom is application-layer: prolonged time to first byte and occasional timeouts specifically on web_server_0.\n\n4) Load balancer and backend isolation\n- Load balancer network config:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 (server farm VLAN), default route via 10.200.0.1\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (private backend link)\n- The backend subnet (20.200.0.0/24) is present only on the LB side; hosts do not have routes to it, consistent with “backend web servers should not be directly accessible.” No evidence of client reachability to backend subnet.\n- From clients, web99.local performance is stable, suggesting load balancer function and backend connectivity are healthy.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Intermittent HTTP performance degradation limited to web0.local (10.200.0.3):\n  - Multiple client-side connection attempts experienced TTFB delays of 6–8 seconds and outright 10s timeouts, while other servers and the load balancer were consistently fast.\n  - Subsequent tests to the same server showed normal behavior, implying transient or intermittent issue.\n- Cosmetic resolver behavior on dns_server:\n  - The local “host” utility attempted IPv6 ::1 and reported “address not available” before succeeding over IPv4. Clients are unaffected; this is a local resolver/tool behavior.\n\nFault localization\n- The problem domain is localized to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) and its HTTP application stack:\n  - Network path (L3, DNS, switching/routing) does not indicate issues.\n  - NIC/interface/queueing on web_server_0 shows no drops or errors.\n  - Other servers in the same subnet and via the same network path do not exhibit similar slowdowns at the time of testing.\n\nProbable root cause\n- Application-layer slowness or stalls on web_server_0’s HTTP service (python3 listener on port 80), causing intermittent long time to first byte and occasional client timeouts. This is unlikely to be caused by DNS or L3 transport issues given quick lookups, low-latency ICMP, and lack of packet loss/drops.\n\nNon-issues confirmed\n- OSPF routing appears stable (consistent end-to-end reachability and latencies).\n- DHCP appears to have assigned client IPs properly (hosts present with 10.1.1.10 and 10.2.1.10).\n- The load balancer and backend isolation are consistent with design intent; no direct client access to backend network observed.\n\nEnd of report (no remediation actions included by request).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 14145, "output_tokens": 4764, "total_tokens": 18909, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 13952}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3136}}}
